  "text": "Prometheus enforces TLS and authentication compliance for remote write endpoints through a multi-layered validation and implementation approach:\n\n## Configuration Validation (config/config.go)\n\nThe primary enforcement occurs in `config/config.go` at two key points:\n\n1. **RemoteWriteConfig.UnmarshalYAML()** (line 1447-1478): This validation method is called during YAML config parsing and enforces:\n   - URL validation (must not be empty)\n   - Header validation via `validateHeaders()` - prevents users from manually setting Authorization header\n   - HTTPClientConfig validation via `c.HTTPClientConfig.Validate()` - validates TLS configuration\n   - Authentication configuration validation via `validateAuthConfigs()`\n\n2. **validateAuthConfigs()** (line 1490-1515): This function ensures that only ONE of the following authentication methods is configured:\n   - basic_auth\n   - authorization (Bearer token)\n   - oauth2\n   - sigv4 (AWS SigV4)\n   - azuread (Azure AD)\n   - google_iam (Google IAM)\n   This prevents conflicting or misconfigured authentication.\n\n3. **validateHeaders()** (line 1529-1539): This function validates custom headers by:\n   - Preventing the Authorization header from being manually set (users must use proper auth config fields)\n   - Preventing reserved headers from being overridden (host, content-type, user-agent, etc.)\n\nSimilarly, **RemoteReadConfig.UnmarshalYAML()** (line 1612-1629) calls the same validation functions to ensure consistency for remote read endpoints.\n\n## Client Creation with TLS (storage/remote/client.go)\n\n1. **NewWriteClient()** (line 182-238): Creates a remote write client with TLS and authentication support:\n   - Calls `config_util.NewClientFromConfig()` with HTTPClientConfig containing TLS settings\n   - Wraps the transport with SigV4, Azure AD, or Google IAM round trippers as configured\n   - These round trippers inject Bearer tokens into the Authorization header during request execution\n\n2. **NewReadClient()** (line 150-180): Creates a remote read client with the same TLS validation and authentication support\n\nThe HTTPClientConfig from prometheus/common library handles the actual TLS certificate validation, CA bundle loading, and HTTPS enforcement.\n\n## Configuration Application (storage/remote/write.go)\n\n**WriteStorage.ApplyConfig()** (line 137-200): Applies the validated remote write configuration:\n- Creates NewWriteClient instances with the validated RemoteWriteConfig\n- Passes HTTPClientConfig containing TLS settings to the client factory\n- Updates existing clients when configuration changes, including secret changes\n\n## Authentication Implementation\n\nAuthentication enforcement is handled by specialized round trippers:\n\n1. **Azure AD Authentication** (storage/remote/azuread/azuread.go):\n   - `AzureADConfig.Validate()` (line 130-220) validates Azure-specific auth config\n   - `azureADRoundTripper.RoundTrip()` (line 259-269) injects Bearer token with format: \"Bearer \" + accessToken\n   - Supports multiple Azure auth methods: Managed Identity, Workload Identity, OAuth, SDK\n\n2. **Google IAM Authentication** (storage/remote/googleiam/googleiam.go):\n   - `NewRoundTripper()` (line 32-54) creates a transport with Google Cloud authentication\n   - Uses Google Cloud Application Default Credentials for token management\n\n## Summary\n\nThe compliance enforcement chain is: Configuration YAML → RemoteWriteConfig.UnmarshalYAML validation → validateAuthConfigs/validateHeaders → HTTPClientConfig.Validate() → NewWriteClient creation → config_util.NewClientFromConfig (TLS setup) → Authentication round trippers injecting Bearer tokens. This ensures that remote write endpoints must be configured with either HTTPS/TLS and at least one of the supported authentication methods, preventing insecure communication and misconfigured credentials."
}

